h 47. A ‘missa in pascha annotina' is inserted between Low Sunday (Dic Octabas Pascha) and the Second Sunday aster Easter (Dom. 1 post Oct. Pasch.) ⁸.

This ‘Pascha annotinum,’ kept on or near Low Sunday, denoted the solemn and public renewal oi their baptismal vows on the part ol those who had been baptized at Easter-tide in the preceding year ⁹. From the rubric in the margin it seems to have been a fixed day which might fall in Lent. The rubric is written in the later hand, and shows that the ceremony had not become obsolete in the eleventh century in England ¹⁰.
